[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_notrump"]
[Student "S"]
{Because of his 3-4-3-3 distribution, partner chose not to look for a \H fit. If he had opted for Stayman the contract would have turned out the same. The 4NT response is quantitative, inviting you to bid 6NT if you have a maximum.

You do. 6NT.

East plays 6NT. South leads the \SK. You will have to make an early decision on whether to hold up or not.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 3 : \D = 5 : \C = 2 :: Total = 11

Only one more winner is needed. You should play a low \S from dummy in the hope that South will lead the suit again, giving you a trick with your \SJ (you know South holds \SQ). In fact, you should even give him some incentive to play another \S by dropping your \S9, pretending to hold just the \S J 9. But South noticed his partner's discouraging \S2 and switched to the \C8. 

You try the \CJ but North plays the \CQ and you have to win with your \CK. 

Your chances for success are slipping away and you are down to your last hope. Your \SJ is a threat that only South can guard against. If South also is the defender with long \Hs then he would also have to guard dummy's fourth \H. In that case you could squeeze him. But there is one important play you must make for the squeeze to function. 

You must play dummy's \SA to unblock so your \SJ can be the threat you need. Then play the \HA, \CA and 5 \D winners. 

If South has thrown the \SQ you win your \SJ and dummy's two high \Hs. But since he probably held onto the \SQ you just play a \H to dummy and hope all three \Hs are winners.

Since South had to guard both the \Hs and your \SJ, he was unable to do both, and the squeeze worked.

You were lucky it wasn't North with the 4 \Hs.}
[Play "W"]SK

